docs.abstract: IBM researchers used an exotic material known as a Weyl semimetal to confirm the existence of a gravitational anomaly predicted in equations that describe the universe.
docs.snippet: IBM researchers used an exotic material known as a Weyl semimetal to confirm the existence of a gravitational anomaly predicted in equations that describe the universe.
docs.lead_paragraph: The equations that describe the universe at the smallest and largest scales — how the tiniest elementary particles dance, how the space-time of the cosmos bends — predicted a slight incongruity, a tiny unbalancing in the numbers of certain particles under certain circumstances.

headline.main: An Experiment in Zurich Brings Us Nearer to a Black Hole’s Mysteries
headline.print_headline: Ribbon Cutting: A Mystery With Practical Implications

docs.abstract: As some American companies pull back from hiring programmers a world away, new tech jobs are cropping up across the country.
docs.snippet: As some American companies pull back from hiring programmers a world away, new tech jobs are cropping up across the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: For years, American companies have been saving money by “offshoring” jobs — hiring people in India and other distant cubicle farms.

headline.main: Hot Spot for Tech Outsourcing: The United States
headline.print_headline: That Job Sent to India May Now Go to Indiana
